definition.value: This is an AE which is a mass of  all the tissue in the body that is not hardened by the processes of ossification or calcification such as bones and teeth.
This is an AE which is a malignant tumour, a type of cancer, that develops in soft tissue.
This is an AE which is the partial or complete wasting away of a part of the soft tissue.
This is an AE which is part of the complex biological response of soft tissue to harmful stimuli.
This is an AE which is a type of abnormal and excessive growth of soft tissue.
This is an AE which refers a transient abnormal enlargement of soft tissue not caused by a tumor.
This is an AE which is  rupture of  the fibrous connective tissue that connects bones to other bones.
This is an AE which is the stretching or tearing of ligaments within a joint, often caused by an injury abruptly forcing the joint beyond its functional range of motion.
This is an AE which is a cause of chronic body pain characterized by loose ligaments.
This is an AE which is a disorder of  the fibrous connective tissue that connects bones to other bones.
This is an AE which is any disease that has the connective tissues of the body as a target of pathology.
This is an AE which refers to any joint disease of the vertebral column.
This is an AE which is a spinal of  posterior displacement of one vertebral body with respect to the subjacent vertebra to a degree less than a luxation (dislocation).
This is an AE which is a physical anomaly that is deleterious, i.e. a structural defect perceived as a problem such as spine malformation.
This is an AE which is a birth defect in which there is incomplete closing of the spine and the membranes around the spinal cord during early development in pregnancy.
This is an AE which is a mass on the part of the axial skeleton.
This is an AE which feels pain of a small membranous protrusion from a neuron's dendrite.
This is an AE which is an inflammation of the vertebrae.
This is an AE which is a form of gait abnormality.
This is an AE which is nominally referred to as any variation of standard human gait, typically manifesting as a coping mechanism in response to an anatomical impairment.
This is an AE which is characterised by an inability to initiate the process of walking, despite the power and coordination of the legs being normal when tested in the seated or lying position.
This is an AE which is nominally referred to as any variation of standard human gait, typically manifesting as a coping mechanism in response to an anatomical impairment.
This is an AE which is the inflammation of the fluid-filled sheath (called the synovium) that surrounds a tendon, typically leading to joint pain, swelling, and stiffness.
This is an AE which can occur in apparently healthy subjects having no atypical appearance and who may be unaware of carrying risk.
This is an AE which is a rare neurologic disorder of unclear cause characterized by progressive rigidity and stiffness.
This is an AE which is an uncommon focal variant of the stiff person syndrome and is characterized by stiffness and painful spasms of the lower limbs, with no axial involvement.
This is an AE which is defined as arthritis affecting two to four joints during the first six months of disease.
This is an AE which refers to a height of a human which is below typical.
This is an AE which is a limitation on a person's physical functioning, mobility, dexterity or stamina.
This is an AE which is any intentional act causing injury or trauma to another person or animal by way of bodily contact.
This is an AE which is the removal of a leg by trauma, medical illness, or surgery.
This is an AE which is a deviation from normal walking (gait).
This is an AE which is one of the most widespread and impactful consequences of multiple sclerosis (MS).
This is an AE which is a condition in which one or more fingers become permanently bent in a flexed position.
This is an AE which is a heterogeneous group of disorders characterized by abnormal thickening of the stratum corneum of the palms and soles.
This is an AE which is a bleeding into joint spaces. It is a common feature of hemophilia.
This is an AE which is very frequent and usually self limited to a few weeks.
This is an AE which is a form of osteoarthritis following an injury to a joint.
This is an AE which should be regarded as infectious until proved otherwise.
This is an AE which is inflammation within the sacroiliac joint.
This is an AE which is recurring pain symptoms that are relatively common in children ages 3 to 12.
This is an AE which is an abnormality of the hip joint where the socket portion does not fully cover the ball portion, resulting in an increased risk for joint dislocation.
This is an AE which is an infection with arthritis caused by the rubella virus.
This is an AE which is the invasion of a joint by an infectious agent streptococcal resulting in joint inflammation.
This is an AE which is the invasion of a joint by an infectious agent haemophilus resulting in joint inflammation.
This is an AE which is associated with conditions such as clubfoot, cerebral palsy, and myelodysplasia.
This is an AE which is a class of joint disorder (called arthropathy) that is characterized by accumulation of tiny crystals in one or more joints.
This is an AE which is an abnormality of the hip joint where the socket portion does not fully cover the ball portion, resulting in an increased risk for joint dislocation.
This is an AE which is a major abnormality in the shape of hip compared to the normal shape of that part.
This is an AE which is a disease in which the body mistakenly attacks its own tissues.
